<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Sami_flag.svg" class="image" title="Sami flag"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Sami_flag.svg/200px-Sami_flag.svg.png" width="200" height="149" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Sami_flag.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Sami_flag" title="Sami flag">Sami flag</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>Sámi people</b>, (also known as <b>Lapps</b>, although this term is considered derogatory<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup>) are the <a href="/wiki/Indigenous_people" title="Indigenous people" class="mw-redirect">indigenous people</a> <a href="/wiki/Indigenous_peoples_of_Europe" title="Indigenous peoples of Europe" class="mw-redirect">of northern Europe</a> inhabiting <a href="/wiki/S%C3%A1pmi_(area)" title="Sápmi (area)">Sápmi</a>, which today encompasses parts of northern <a href="/wiki/Sweden" title="Sweden">Sweden</a>, <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norway</a>, <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Kola_Peninsula" title="Kola Peninsula">Kola Peninsula</a> of <a href="/wiki/Russia" title="Russia">Russia</a>. Their ancestral lands span an area the size of Sweden in the <a href="/wiki/Nordic_countries" title="Nordic countries">Nordic countries</a>. The Sámi people are among the largest indigenous ethnic groups in <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>. Their traditional languages are the <a href="/wiki/S%C3%A1mi_languages" title="Sámi languages" class="mw-redirect">Sámi languages</a>, which are classified as members of the <a href="/wiki/Finno-Lappic" title="Finno-Lappic" class="mw-redirect">Finno-Lappic</a> group of the <a href="/wiki/Uralic_languages" title="Uralic languages">Uralic</a> language family.</p>
<p>Traditionally, the Sámi have plied a variety of livelihoods, including coastal fishing, <a href="/wiki/Fur_trapping" title="Fur trapping" class="mw-redirect">fur trapping</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Shepherd" title="Shepherd">sheep herding</a>. However, the best known Sami livelihood is semi-nomadic <a href="/wiki/Reindeer" title="Reindeer">reindeer</a> herding - which about 10% of the Sámi are connected with and 2,800 actively involved with full-time.<sup id="cite_ref-galdu.org_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-galdu.org-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> For traditional, cultural, and political reasons, reindeer herding is legally reserved only for Sámi people in certain regions of the Nordic countries.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6" title=""><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> The Sámi in general, however, lead usual contemporary lives in villages and cities inside and outside <a href="/wiki/S%C3%A1pmi" title="Sápmi" class="mw-redirect">Sápmi</a>, and hold the same kind of jobs as everyone else in their states.</p>
<p><br /></p>
